			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				With all of the talk about philosphy, religion and what not I think I have the perfect book for everybody to read:
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/086171380X/qid=1113963634/sr=1-1/ref=sr_1_1/002-9404367-7668041?v=glance&amp;s=books" target="_blank" class="postlink">Hardcore Zen : Punk Rock, Monster Movies, &amp; the Truth about Reality</a>
<br />

<br />
At first I thought it was yet another poser wannabe western new-age book and I picked it up with a smirk on my face.  After I read the first chapter I couldn't put it down.  This is one of the best book that gives a great foundation to Zen Buddhist philosphy.  The author was a punk rocker in the 1970s and 1980s then 'discovered' Zen in college.  He has a pretty strong lineage; his college Zen instructor was instructed by a student of Shunryu Suzuki, whom you all probably never heard of but he is (was) a big deal.  He then studied in Tokyo for eleven or so years under the guidence of a man named Gudo Nishijima, whom if I remember correctly was the first person to translate the Shobogenzo into English.  The Shobogenzo is about the closest you can get to a Zen "bible."
<br />
My point in mentioning this stuff is that his guy is the real deal and not just some half assed wannabe philospher yet being an American he really put stuff in perspective.
<br />

<br />
Outside of the Buddhist philosophies, the author make some great comments about society as well as really neat stories of him as a kid growing up in the punk scene.
<br />

<br />
Here are a few excerpts that I typed out:
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Question authority.  Question society.  Question reality.
<br />
But you've got to take it all the way:  Question punk authority.  Question punk society.  Question your own rules and question your own values.  Question Zen society.  Question Zen authority.  Question other people's views on reality and question your own.
<br />
No matter what authority you submit to - your teacher, your government, even Jesus H. Christ or Gautama Buddha himself - that authority is wrong.  It's wrong because the very concept of authority is already a mistake.  Deffering to authority is nothing more than  a cowardly shirking of personal responsibility.  The more power you grant an authority figure the worse you can behave in his name.  That's why people who take God as their ultimate authority are always capable of the worst humanity has to offer.  Zen does not accept anything even resembling that kind of God.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Another:
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
I love the covers of thsoe New Age books that show some Enlightened Saint with blue halos around his body, shining pure white light from his head and fingertips.  It's pure crap.  A real enlightened being doesn't look any different from anyone else.  They're just ordinary people like you.  The other stuff's just special effects. . . Enlightenment is reality itself.
<br />
And reality is you - naked, stinky , and phony as all get out.
<br />
Reality doesn't know a damn thing.
<br />
Reality has doubts and insecurities.
<br />
Reality gets horny sometimes and sometimes reality likes to read the funny pages.
<br />
Reality is an old guy in Cleveland Heights complaining that his grandkids have stolen his dentures again.
<br />
Reality is five guys trying to tune three guitars and a Farfisa compact organ to the same pitch and failing misearbly.
<br />
Reality is teh source of every star, every planet, every galaxy; every dust mote, every atom; every klepton, lepton, and slepton.
<br />
Reality is the basis of every booger up your nose, every pit-stain in your dad's t-shirts, and every dingleberry on your %@$#.
<br />
Reality is this moment.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I was going to type out some more stuff, but his entire book is so good I wouldn't know where to stop.  I can not recommend this book enough.  Even if you do not give a rat's %@$# what Zen Buddhism is all about his book is a great read about society and philsophy in general.
<br />

<br />
He also has a pretty good website <a href="http://homepage.mac.com/doubtboy/" target="_blank" class="postlink">HERE</a>.  Even has some movie reviews.  At the very least I think you all should read his online articles.  I think some of you would really dig his review of "Kill Bill."<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
